column1: Currently, there are no truly free open source synthetic biology toolkits for engineering yeast. This inhibits innovation and restricts access to these powerful organisms as platforms for biotechnology. The Open Yeast Collection is a free and open DNA toolkit for engineering Saccharomyces cerevisiae and Pichia pastoris, enabling anyone to have a complete and robust toolkit to build new metabolic pathways or produce enzymes and proteins of interest.

Click on column headers for more information as to what to put into the column

column1: Short and human friendly name for the part, e.g., "GFP Reporter"
column2: This is the role of the part according to the sequence ontology (see Ontology tab for full list). Select from the drop down menu or type have it validated.
column3: Comments about design decisions. E.g. GC content or restriction sites removed
column4: If no changes were made use Direct, otherwise say changes that were made (can choose for drop down menu)
column5: A description of how the part is meant to function and any information about the part that is not to do with how it was designed.
column6: Where is the information about this part coming from? Provide a tag and e.g. AG for an Addgene plasmid. Tags found in the Source Sheet
column7: Where is the information about this part coming from? Provide a te.g. 87906 for an Addgene plasmid. This is interpreted together with the column to the left
column8: Where is the genetic information coming from, e.g. gene taken from Aequorea victoria if available add in strain name too. This should match the scientific name for the txid in the next column
column9: Where will the part be used, e.g. construct for use in Escherichia coli 98NK2. Where available include the strain name. This should match the scientific name for the txid in the next column
column10: True if this is a final product to be produced, false if this is an intermediate stage being specified for compactness
column11: Whether or not the part is circular. Select TRUE (circular) or FALSE (linear).
column12: Automatically calculated length of the sequence pasted to the right. Use this column for checking there are no paste errors.
column13: The series of ATGCs that make up the part. Spaces can be used within the sequence but no other characters.

Geranyl pyrophosphate (GPP) synthase produces geranyl pyrophosphate (GPP) from DMAPP and IPP. GPP is the universal C10 precursor of the monoterpenes.
Geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGPP) synthase catalyzes the synthesis of Geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGPP) from farnesyl diphosphate and isopentenyl diphosphate.
Farnesyl pyrophosphate synthase

4S-limonene-synthase (EC 4.2.3.16) catalyzes the cyclization of geranyl diphosphate to (‚àí)-(4S)-limonene. Limonene is a relatively stable colorless liquid aliphatic hydrocarbon classified as a cyclic monoterpene, and is the is a major component of the aromatic scents such as in the oil of citrus fruit peels.
(‚àí)-Limonene-3-hydroxylase (L3OH), using O2 and NADPH, catalyzes the allylic hydroxylation of (‚àí)-limonene at the 3 position to (‚àí)-trans-isopiperitenol.
Linalool synthase (LIS) produces (S)-linalool from geranyl diphosphate and water. Linalool is a naturally occurring terpene alcohol found in many flowers and spice plants.

(-)-isopiperitenol/(-)-carveol dehydrogenase is capable of utilizing (‚àí)-trans-isopiperitenol in peppermint and (‚àí)-trans-carveol in spearmint. Carveol is a natural unsaturated, monocyclic monoterpenoid alcohol that is a constituent of spearmint essential oil in the form of cis-(‚àí)-carveol.
(R)-limonene synthase (EC 4.2.3.20) catalyzes the synthesis of (+)-(4R)-limonene from GPP. This enzyme occurs in Citrus, Carum (caraway) and Anethum (dill).
